<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    Re: the namedroppers list policy
From:       <a href="?a=95837693400032&r=1&w=2">Ken Harrenstien &lt;KLH () SRI-NIC ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198708">1987-08-04 10:30:57</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926908&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926908&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Let's be reasonable.  There is really no other list which is so
directly involved with the issues of naming things, and there are
still some real issues that will need tackling.  The fact that these
issues are more political than technical is no reason to deny their
existence; after all, it is politics that determines whether the
domain name system will exist!

For example, as a NIC person I thought the discussion of how to name
NICs was a worthwhile airing of views.

If you still feel strongly that NAMEDROPPERS should remain a sacred
technical list, then we can generate almost twice as much mail and
confusion by starting another list, to wit NAMECALLERS, and make its
initial membership be everyone on NAMEDROPPERS.  Those who don't like
that sort of discussion can then elect to become droppednames.
I'm willing to set up this list.
-------

